Hmm, I suppose you wouldn't be shocked to learn I love animals and nature?
Luckily there's nothing small about getting to know someone like you. There's little occasion for frivolity in nature - I can appreciate your stance... even if others do not.

EditorData.NodeContext: Open-minded and unfazed by Lae'zel's gruff response.

Text.Value: Time can prove to be a trickster on one's recollections - what would be multiple lifetimes for others now separate me from my captivity... perhaps I have lost perspective on what happened to me.

Leave.
Perhaps our time has not yet come. Perhaps dealing with the Absolute must come first. Whatever you decide, I will understand.
This city troubles me... but I am here for you. I want to be by your side, and see this through.

I'm not sure if this is a fond memory or a cautionary tale.
Misadventures in the Underdark? Come on, tell me all.
Tell me something about yourself that I wouldn't even think to ask.

Text.Value: Then... very well. This chapter is at an end. I can only hope you have many more, each filled with happiness.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: You worship Shar? That umbral witch unleashed a plague of darkness on nature - her followers slew many of my fellow druids.
Maybe I have a sweet tooth too.
...I took my chance and fled while all were distracted. I never looked back until I breathed fresh air again, and never learned what came of my hosts.
I have been gifted with the Slayer, a form most evil.
Poor Yenna... How are you holding up?
You know where to find me. Take care.
I see... if that is truly your desire, then I shall respect it. No matter how much I wish it was not the case.
Some drow abhor surface elves. I'm surprised your pelt didn't end up decorating a banquet hall in Menzoberranzan.
Ornaments, utensils - and ducks. I like ducks.
Perhaps fate will afford us more time together - I hope it does.
I want to talk about what happened.

Text.Value: Only by reputation. She was present when we marched against Ketheric Thorm, but on the far end of the battle lines from where I fought.
I see... Foolhardy, perhaps, to reveal such a thing to a veteran of battles against Shar worshippers. Foolhardy... or brave.
I don't think there's anything worth sharing.
You have a habit of getting captured - did you ever notice that?
You are... nothing if not inventive. I can only hope the foe had already expired before you began your work.
Well they are fierce creatures from what I understand... but as long as you avoid the high seas, I think you can consider yourself safe.
I'll help however you wish.
I once stitched shut a wound using twine made from the entrails of an enemy.
I live in mortal fear of krakens, though I've never actually seen one.
Honestly, I never thought I'd make it that far. But the Absolute is a threat to all, and I promised I'd help you with your parasite.
... interesting. Part of me still thought of them as hosts, but I suppose captors is indeed more accurate.
Given the circumstances? You're faring as well as can be expected, I suppose.
I am sorry about Yenna. I wish things had gone differently.
I would have stayed. The populace could do with a show. Take their minds off things.
At least now we can benefit from her presence, and perhaps work to a common goal.
You didn't answer the part about lovers.
No matter how long I live, I will never get used to the cruelties that infest our world. That such evil is allowed to breathe the same air as us is an abomination.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sorrowful (Yenna was an orphan girl who sheltered at the player's camp)

Text.Value: No matter how long I live, I will always strive to remain a keen pupil. Only a fool would think he could drink in all knowledge until none is left. There is always more - nature's tapestry is infinitely complex.
Perhaps a bed next time. Just to be different.
I am lucky to have your counsel. It was sorely needed.
You thought she was an imposter - a threat. This was a trap of Orin's creation. Yenna's death is on her hands, not yours.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sorrowful, but understanding (Yenna was an orphan girl who sheltered at the player's camp)

Text.Value: I really don't know very much about myself to tell.
I have been gifted with the Slayer, a form most evil.
Was there something else you wanted, my heart?
Trust me, the day I no longer have to talk about the shadow curse will be a happy one. What would you like to know?
It was intense. In a good way.
...and still it draws them in. The safety of numbers. The promise of civilisation. The dream of better.
I'll be right here in camp. Take care out there.
Bhaal has chosen me to conquer all of existence in his name. You would be wise to bow.
A short night, at that. I am sorry if I came on too strongly. Take all the time and space you require.
Impressive that she managed to move my bulk, come to think of it. I wonder how that was managed.
Let's take things slowly, for now.
Ha! Talented from the beginning, then? Almost a surprise you didn't cast magic in the womb.
Tough choices lie ahead. This is no time for bleeding hearts.
Oh. Well, your choice, of course.
Three years? That's awful.
Don't misunderstand me - I feared for my life, and wanted my freedom back, but I was willing to wait for my moment, and eventually it came.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: And I have been evicted from the very place I was charged to safeguard. A telling summary of my time as Archdruid, perhaps...
We should return to camp when we can - I must see how Thaniel is faring. With the Oak Father's blessing, the shadow curse may soon be no more.
I cast my first spell whilst still a babe. My mother took an awful fright when I conjured up a score of rabbits in the pantry.
I am sorry, but it's over between us.
I outgrew cynicism around the age of 200. I offer no apologies for my desires.
It was certainly different. But I have no regrets.
That's enough for now.
I need you by my side.
You are right. But I must not lose focus until everything has been put right. I've wasted too much time already - years in which nature has suffered.

EditorData.NodeContext: Conceding a point, but remains hard on himself

Text.Value: It's not for me to say - I wasn't there. But I'm here now, if you wish to talk.
Who is to say? Perhaps there's a half-orc buried somewhere in my ancestry?
It is done - now Thaniel will be whole again. I could not have done this without you, my friend.

EditorData.logicalname: Right after reuniting Oliver and Thaniel

Text.Value: Thaniel still needs our help - part of his essence must still be out there, somewhere.

EditorData.logicalname: IPRD for right after recruiting Halsin

Text.Value: I am sure they are well used to it. Cramped streets and thin walls make for people adept at ignoring things. You could find yourself more alone in a city than in the deepest woods.
On that note, I need you to stay at camp for now.
I need you by my side.
Consider telling him the truth - that you worship Lady Shar.
I have. He speaks to me during my nightly meditations.
You mentioned something about the Underdark?
I'm sorry for your loss.

Text.Value: I had a friend when I was young, long ago. He played with me in the forests where I grew up... but eventually, I realised no one else had heard of him.
Nice.
Cute.
Aww.
Certain... events transpired, and I found myself a guest of a noble drow house for a time. Well, something between guest, prisoner, and consort, perhaps.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: And in the chaos that ensued, well... our forces were scattered. I led some to safety, but never learned of her fate. I'm glad to hear she survived.
Indeed. I know that all too well.
Indeed... perhaps I carry more resentment than I realise.
My memories are all gone. Did your research into the tadpoles suggest that might be a symptom?
Are you still content at my side? This doesn't have to be your fight, and it's certainly not your typical habitat.
...I must be careful, or I'll lose the run of myself again. An Archdruid should show some restraint.
It was not ideal... but not without its positives either. I did what was necessary to survive. And perhaps a few things that were less than necessary.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: You said Thaniel is missing part of himself - any ideas how we can find it?

You are a mortal child of Bhaal? Be careful with whom you share that fact - I hear many of your kind have met premature ends.
Perhaps.

A very likely outcome - in fact I saw decorations of that very type, and worse, in my time there. But my luck held.

Text.Value: Some can thrive here, yes. But it was never meant for everyone. There should be a choice. Nature should be afforded its chance to offer harmony to those who need it.
The city is like a forest with an overgrown canopy. Light and nourishment cannot penetrate to those who need it the most...
I've been unfair to you - I've had unrealistic expectations of your character ever since I joined you...
Inauspicious? Sounds like you did what you had to, and saved lives.
Trust me, it's been said. You've shown more restraint than most in avoiding the subject until now.
How do you see our relationship?
The mighty bear is an escaped pet, then. I wonder if there is a reward for your return.
Well, in a sense, there was. But no harm done. In fact, one of the drow looked like he was going to pay us towards the end.
Hmm, well, I can only hope I don't disappoint.
Right now? I bed down alone, I'm afraid. Perhaps once I talk less of curses and parasites, my fortunes will improve.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little cheeky, a little self-deprecating

Text.Value: Listen to me, preaching like an initiate in his cups.
Indeed. Confusing slavery with a fond memory is quite the shift in perspective.
And a hard-won freedom at that. Well done.
I thought we would be able to help her. I thought we would be able to keep her safe.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sorrowful (Yenna was an orphan girl who sheltered at the player's camp)

Text.Value: In fact, I think I saw just the sort before, not long after we first came within reach of the shadow curse. Fool that I am, I did not grasp their significance at the time.

EditorData.NodeContext: Moment of realisation. Kicking himself a bit for not putting 2 + 2 together earlier

Text.Value: *Surely he will understand. You've developed a strong bond with him already... but perhaps you've waited too long? The revelation could damage the trust you've built.*
It's a fine dream. Perhaps you can help find the balance.
Nature bows to none. It will fight on and survive, no matter what madness your god has inspired you to undertake.
You have said as much to me before, only to change your mind. I told you your heart is your own, but I do not wish for mine to be toyed with. Are you certain?
It's true, and I can't imagine I helped with that. Sometimes I let the task at hand consume me, and people think I'm obsessed.
I trust your leadership, and respect your decisions... but I truly hope this is not something we come to regret.
Indeed.

Lolth's followers are pitiless. You threaded the needle by surviving.
But still... we all failed that little girl.

I will never forget your part in this. Nor will Thaniel.

I'll find you when I need you.

I would still be there with you now, if the sun hadn't intruded on us, and the city hadn't stirred for the day.
I can imagine. You rode out the storm most admirably.
No.

I don't think those two drow will be forgetting us in a hurry.
How did you escape?
Have you received any word from the grove since the Rite of Thorns?
No, don't say that. Perfect would mean there is nothing left to explore.
You are lucky that we share common purpose. In most other cases, this revelation would put us on opposite sides of the battlefield.
My... some bard could write a stirring love poem about you two. Or a lewd tavern ballad, perhaps.

Text.Value: I wanted to speak to you about the night we spent together.
It's a wonderful feeling, to care for someone so deeply. Treasure it.
*How might he take it? Difficult to say. You have some rapport with him, but is it enough? You won't know for sure until you tell him...*
Just my pride - I can't believe I allowed myself to be knocked unconscious and spirited away like that...
It's a natural question, but I don't have a good answer, I'm afraid. Perhaps there's a half-orc buried somewhere in my ancestry.
Though in truth, I should not be surprised - she was always said to be formidable - and cunning. I could have learned much from her, no doubt.
I knew then that I had to be more than a companion to him. I had to be a protector.
I yearn to kill. I only feel like myself when I'm killing.
I lost friends, confidantes, and had the weight of responsibility bear down on me unrelentingly. There was scant opportunity for self-reflection...
I shall not falter from what must be done, but I cannot ignore what I see, either.

Text.Value: I need you to remain at camp for now.
Turn to other matters.
So how did you escape?
My affliction is no more - I'm finally free.
So do I. But one duty at a time.
Don't take this the wrong way, but you're quite large for an elf.
How are you? You weren't harmed when Orin took you, I hope?
That was my first day as Archdruid. An inauspicious beginning.
I wanted to speak to you about the night we spent together.
Turn to other matters.
We'll have our moment, don't worry.
That was something I had dreamed about for some time... and now I realise just how woefully meagre my dreams were, compared to the reality.
No matter how it's been twisted by the shadows, it is still part of Thaniel's essence - it will resemble him somehow, and may show signs of his power.
None - the grove has cut itself off from the world, to jealously guard its own little pocket of nature. No one shall ever enter or leave again.
Turn to other matters.
My heart soars just to look upon you. What do you need?
Speak to me, lover.
All of nature's bounty pales next to you. Do you need something?
You wish to speak? I am here for you.
The same's true of everyone, I find.
Of course.

Text.Value: Don't mind me. I'm just enjoying the show.
Always.

Come here to me...
No hardship for me. Far from it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Enthused/romantic. Love interest player asked for a kiss.

Text.Value: Indeed. Our time with them was... certainly bracing. Takes me back to some youthful misadventures in the Underdark.
I know, I know; well-trodden territory. Well, let's see... I whittle in my spare time, and I've something of a sweet tooth - though everyone's very amused when I say I like honey.
Don't worry yourself about what I think just yet - we may not have spent much time in each other's company yet, but I joined you because your judgement seems sound.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if no approval check is valid.

Text.Value: When I first met you, saving yourself from ceremorphosis was your greatest wish... yet now you have stepped closer to embracing it.
You're fortunate to know what you like. I wouldn't pay any attention to what others think.
I cannot help but wonder how she would have handled some of the challenges I faced as Archdruid. Defended the grove? Kagha? The Shadow Druids?
Wherever you need me.
Ah, but there are no pets in nature - only companions. Though I'll admit Crag likely made for a rather stoic confidante...
Why would you test my patience like this? Sometimes it is difficult to love you.
I warned you to not broach such matters lightly. Perhaps you care less for me than I supposed...
Does it please you to see me crestfallen? That is the only reason I can think why you might toy with my heart like this.

EditorData.NodeContext: Terse. Angry with a lover who has repeatedly broached the subject of breaking up, only to swerve away from it.

Text.Value: I am aware. Perhaps I put too much faith in my skills of negotiation, or want to see good where there is none.
You have me? Let's not get carried away - circumstance brought us together.
I am open to anything - if you can find a piece of furniture that is up to the challenge.
You're better off with me anyway.

The passage of time has a strange way of polishing even the most arduous of memories into precious keepsakes. Had circumstances been slightly different, I may have been put to work in mines, or killed outright.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: He is well - and Oliver also. At times they are one, and at others they divide. Easier for playing, perhaps. And the land thrives also. I doubt you would recognise it.
The missing part of him must be near there. We need to search that area.
We were as one. The warmth of your skin, the feel of your...
Are you sure? Holding back is not in my nature, but I would not wish to alarm you, or harm you.
You mentioned the Underdark before - come on, tell me about it.
Well, I have something of a soft spot for animals... though I've never had a pet, that I'm aware of.
Sounds traumatic. You may need to reflect on that.
So you turn into a bear and you like honey? A little on the nose.
I don't think those two drow will be forgetting us in a hurry.
Save for me, my line perished a long time ago. They rest in High Forest now, near the shade of the Grandfather Tree. The grove became my family, with Silvanus as my teacher. And now, I have you.
Hold on - nature needs reminding of what exactly?
I need you to remain at camp for now.
How am I holding up in your estimations?
No - I shall not take you for granted, nor my own past. What is the point of long life, if one does not make room for reflection?
Oh, do not be such a cynic, Boo.

EditorData.NodeContext: Preceded by a Boo squeak in response to seeing Halsin and the avatar share a kiss.

Text.Value: Whittling? What do you make?
Oak Father preserve you.
How about another kiss?
Are you still content at my side? This doesn't have to be your fight, and it's certainly not your typical habitat.
Then you'll have me. Lead on.
How are you? You weren't harmed when Orin took you, I hope?
I'm glad we have Jaheira travelling with us. Did you know her from before?
We need to keep our guard up - those brigands got too close to use for my liking.
I wish... I wish there was a better way. I wish everyone could see the sun, have a full belly, and know nature as a friend. There is a balance that is yet to be found.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wistful. Thinking of a dream he's not sure will ever be fulfilled.

Text.Value: But that must wait for now - there are battles yet to be fought. We must save the world before we can dream of ways to better it.
Look for signs of life in the darkness. Wildflowers, where everything else is dead. The curse cannot subdue the power Thaniel bears. Not entirely.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grave. They'll have to effectively kill a child to save a child.

Text.Value: I had heard the municipal laws regarding large animals had been struck down... but still, perhaps we were wise to not push our luck. This time.
Druids and Harpers joined together to put a stop to Ketheric Thorm. We marched on Moonrise and, after much fighting, we prevailed.
You would be unwise to attempt it, trust me. In any case, the house of my captors is long-extinct.
I've always wanted a child of my own. Perhaps one day, when peace visits the Coast.
350 years young. I've been privileged to watch saplings grow into mighty boughs.
Very much so. One positive I will concede about city life is that you never know what lies around the corner.
There are wildflowers growing by an old shack, deep in the shadow curse.
Ha! Pet ownership is an illusion - nature's creatures choose their own companions. No one has true mastery over them in the end. As it should be.
Flowers in bloom where nothing else grows...? That is a sign of Thaniel's power - it must be.

EditorData.NodeContext: alert and intrigued - the breakthrough he's been waiting for

Text.Value: You were not even born when Shar's followers slew my fellow druids, or when her shadow curse tainted the land. I can get past those... but I truly wish you had trusted me sooner.
Is that so? Would you seek to drizzle honey on a neck before indulging?

EditorData.NodeContext: Droll (in response to a vampire indicating they might have a sweet tooth.

Text.Value: I... have not had true confidantes for some time. The Shadow Curse robbed me of almost all my peers, and replaced them with the weight of responsibility. Perhaps that caused me to gild undeserving memories of my youth.
Any time.
I was concerned the City Watch might burst in on us, with the sounds we made.
But it heartens me to learn you and I share the same admiration.
I don't think those two drow will be forgetting us in a hurry.
How did you come to be a druid?
Nature has been most kind to let me share in your heart. What do you need?
You truly are a feast for my eyes - nature outdid itself with you. Did you wish to speak?
I have longed to hear your voice. Speak to me.
What word, my love?

EditorData.NodeContext: Warm/romantic greetings, addressing his partner (secondary partner in a polyamorous relationship, but Halsin makes no real distinction in status)

Text.Value: Most unnatural. Most foul. Nature is a cycle of life and death, yet this form only serves death. Worse - it only serves murder.
I understand my affliction at last - I am a Bhaalspawn. The Lord of Murder compels me.
What do you want?
You wish to speak? Fine.
Oak Father, grant me patience... what do you want?

EditorData.NodeContext: Terse (dislikes the player/has low approval of them)

Text.Value: Honestly...? I'd hoped for more from you. But perhaps things can yet be turned around.
Lolth's noble houses are constantly at each other's throats, and eventually, the house that held me fell out of favour, and was attacked.
Consort?
Relationship? Such terms belong to civilisation - a little unfamiliar to my lips. You know what we share is more fluid, more founded in the principles of nature.
There is a ruin, some way outside of Last Light. I caught a glimpse of fresh blooms there, but did not investigate further. I shall mark it upon your map.

EditorData.NodeContext: Eager/determined. They have a promising lead

Text.Value: We don't have to talk about it, if you don't want to.
I was concerned the City Watch might burst in on us, thinking a bear was running amok, devouring flesh.
All that potential is too often destined to die in the dark, and rot in the gutter.

Well, I didn't pick this scar up in battle. I was in wildshape, only I forgot it was the season when bears are particularly social. A she-bear claimed me as her own - and did not appreciate being spurned.
What happened before, when the shadow curse was unleashed?
My mind still drifts to that dream I shared with you, for a better future for all those who need it... but that must wait. I remain yours, of course. Ready when you need me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly distracted by world events, but glad to be with the player (romantic partner)

Text.Value: Lolth's noble houses are constantly at each other's throats, and eventually, some rivals of my hosts sought to unseat them.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: It would be easy to resort to nature's fury whenever something stood in my way, yet I cannot help but feel I would be sullying the Oak Father's gifts. Naive perhaps... but I still draw breath.
Still, though... this place crawls with life, but little of it flourishes. I see refugees, unhoused. The destitute, unwanted. Orphans, unloved.
Farewell.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: Still, perhaps I can yet serve nature in another way, once our journey has ended. I can only pray that the Oak Father grants me new purpose.
I didn't expect such naivety in an Archdruid of your vintage.
With the end upon us? So long as I am surviving, and I have you by my side, I am faring as well as anyone can be.

EditorData.NodeContext: to love interest player during the climactic sequence of the game.

Text.Value: You're right. But the work is not yet done - not while Ketheric Thorm still draws breath.

EditorData.NodeContext: Conceding a point, but remains hard on himself

Text.Value: *A terrible idea, surely. He barely tolerates you as it is - the chances that he'll show understanding are vanishingly slim.*
This is my home you're talking about - it's not some pit of despair.
I just wanted to see how you were faring.
I'm afraid there's not much I can say - I've sworn confidence to someone already.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if a non-avatar tries to speak to Halsin.

Text.Value: Hmm... it seems the way to camp is unavailable to me just now.
That was terrible.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: I don't think those two drow will be forgetting us in a hurry.
Of course.
...but honestly? You've surpassed even those. Seems my faith was more than well-founded.
You're right. I should not let the failures of the past sour the victories of the present. We have achieved something immense here.

EditorData.NodeContext: Conceding a point. He's helped do a lot of good.

Text.Value: I yearn to kill. I only feel like myself when I'm killing.
Any idea how that came about?
I hope so. But I won't turn my back on the past - it made me who am I today.
Have you had any contact with Thaniel since we left him?
May I kiss you?
Nothing half as charming as that... it's all crimson and rot.
Do you have people out there somewhere? Family? Friends? A lover, perhaps?
I feel closer to nature, now that nature's been inside me.
A Shar worshipper... I see. It can't have been easy for you to tell me such a thing, given my history. But I am glad you took the plunge.
Thank me by returning the favour, why don't you? Come on - I've sure you've got all sorts you could tell me.
Actually, never mind. Stay with me.
Turn to other matters.
I have no love for your goddess, or the foul things she unleashed upon nature. But I can appreciate your honesty. There is nobility in your conduct, if not in your allegiance.
Don't worry. I have strong tastes and a big appetite.
I remember you spoke harshly about drow once. Perhaps this explains that.
Consider telling him the truth - that you worship Lady Shar.
I'm glad you enjoyed yourself.
Of course... That is your right.
The urge to kill is common in nature - for some creatures it is the core of their being... Still, though, you seem to speak of a darker impulse. Be careful how it manifests itself.
You speak nothing but truths.
We're all adults here. Though some of us may be walking a little stiffly for a while...
There must be no more Yennas.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sorrowful/determined (Yenna was an orphan girl who sheltered at the player's camp)

Text.Value: Don't leave me hanging - is there someone in your life right now?
I think I know how you feel... duty, eh? I hope your wish comes true. We'll need new life once all this is over.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little wistful. 'I get it' smile on 'duty, eh?'

Text.Value: When I first got to the Hells, I was so scared and lonely I adopted a pet rock. Named it Crag.
You're not a doppelganger, are you? Trying to study me, learn all my secrets so you can take my place?
It was Thaniel, of course. Nature was my very first friend. I get older, but he hasn't changed a day.
Think nothing of it.
Perhaps this was all a mistake. I don't think we should continue.
I'm 350 years old. Of course there have been lovers. Just because I love nature doesn't mean I'm betrothed to it. Though sometimes, nature needs reminding...
You are right. But such... drastic times can make it difficult to preserve nuance in one's thinking. Further reflection is needed.
Indeed, I am but one of your lovers. You and I should each seek happiness, wherever it lies. You are all I want, but I will not hoard you to myself. Let others know the happiness of being with you.
You'll make a decent workhorse. This camp doesn't haul itself around each day.
You're right. Sometimes I think people look at me and imagine my feelings can't be hurt.
The house matron took an interest in me, and the patron also... They saw me as a novelty, perhaps. I was chained in their bedchamber for nigh on three years.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recounting an episode from a lively youth. Neither bragging nor ashamed

Text.Value: Indeed. Thank you for inviting me. I hadn't realised you considered me a worthy accomplice in such matters. I hope you'll keep me in mind, in future.
Of course. I only wish you'd joined me earlier.
I think our relationship has run its course.
Nor I. At my age, I've come to see that little is worth regretting in the long run, apart from regrets themselves.
I feel like I haven't gotten to know you properly yet.
I wanted to try and find him, but we couldn't stay - we would have all succumbed. When the Archdruid of the Grove - my predecessor - was seized by the curse, I had to lead the survivors to safety.
You've spent all these years fighting the shadow curse - what happens once it's lifted?
What would you like to know?
Always.

EditorData.NodeContext: Medium intensity - this is a 'backfill node' we want so we can use it to patch holes we might find in our dialogues at a later date if needed. Therefore, the context is very broad.

Text.Value: Apologies, I meant no offence. I survived, and in years to come, I must have allowed hardships to become dwarfed by the Shadow Curse in my mind.
Thank you for sharing.
We have challenges to surmount, of course, but with you by my side, my heart stays strong.

Synopsis: Halsin's default in-party dialogue once you have him available as a companion. You recruit/dismiss him, and discuss an assortment of topics with him.
